A perennial favorite in the SF pizza scene.

Twinkle twinkle. Whenever I think of deep dish pizza, I imagine an abominable amount of grease gushing out every orifice... but I was pleasantly surprised that Little Star's pizza turned out to be very fresh and not over the top. Try it with the cornmeal crust. Mammamia!

We spent the day downtown and were exhausted, but famished. Since we are staying near the convention center, we decided to eat at a local place where we could walk and enjoy the neighborhood. I can't say enough about this place.  It's my favorite spot in the South loop and dare I say the best Italian restaurant in the Chicago!...  I'm Sicilian so I have the credibility to make this statement ;).    It reminds me of food my grandma would serve but slightly elevated. My husband and I go almost every Friday and sit at the bar, and the service is fantastic.   They have food specials and also a great Happy Hour from 3-6PM with food and drinks.  I'm a vegetarian, so my favorite items are escarole & beans, manicotti, brussels sprouts with bacon on the side (for the hubs), all their veggies sides ... and their thin crust pizza.  They accommodate special requests and are also vegan friendly. especially if you like pasta and veggies.   Their veggies are so fresh... sounds like an odd observation, but it makes a difference.  They're famous for their meatballs, which my husband and others ... say the fame is warranted.  I have no doubt, whatever you chose you will have a tasty meal.

Dining at quite a few places in Chicago I've rarely had a bad experience, especially with Italian.  This time around was one of those exceptions.  The atmosphere is  typical Chicago, stuffed, loud,  crowded seating arrangements and dim lighting.  The walls are adorned with actors from the 50s and 60s.  The food is served in very large portions (a Caeser salad feeds two and a half people easily) for a decent price.  My wife liked her lasagna well enough, but wasn't blown away.  My Orrechiette pasta was dry and lacked flavor.  Service was also a bit slow although our waitress was nice and accommodating enough (I believe she just had too many tables). Couldn't even use conversation as a filler because we couldn't hear each other talk! Totally unacceptable. They really do need to be less greedy about stuffing people in, as this last experience will be our last. And they turned my original 4 rating into a 2!

We arrived at a good time, right before the late dinner rush.  And I am glad we did.  Once we were seated, you can see the tables start to fill and the bar area was packed.  So for me sitting here waiting to order, this was a good sign (+1). For starters, the awesome waitress recommended this fried eggplant salad built like a caprese.  I thought, ok, sounds weird but if you're recommending it, sounds like a great starter.  Nailed it!  Tons of flavor across the board; fresh greens, lightly breaded eggplant, seasoned well... we are off to a good start. As we are watching the food go by, we cannot keep our eyes on the menu.  What did they have, that looks delicious!  Meatballs are the size of a clincher (A Chicagoan will know what these are).  So aromatic as well.  The table next to use ordered a pizza.  They said they come here once a week for the same pie (+2).  To no avail, I ordered a pizza and the gf orders the spaghetti and meatballs.  No disappointments. I always order a pizza extra crispy but not burnt.  They delivered.  Awesome crust, not too little or too much cheese and good amount of toppings.  And,  I think this pizza is a good size for someone with a healthy appetite and whose date wants to steal a piece or two.  Between our two dishes, the red sauces are to die for!  The meatballs are a splendid addition to the pasta.  The gf split her dish into two; eat here and doggy bag.  She knew right off the bat there was no way to eat the whole thing and remain comfortable.  But really, it was just to save room for the homemade tiramisu.  If you are a tiramisu person, you need to try it. If you are seated in the back of the restaurant, take a look at the specials board on the wall, this seemed like a popular ordering post. All in all, we will be back.  Great setting for a casual get together with friends, but swanky enough if you want to go somewhere on a date night.  Enjoy the Victory in the south loop of Chicago!

I expected to love this place -- good Italian food, great location, classic decor -- and would have enjoyed my experience if it hadn't been so LOUD. We sat in the rear of the restaurant away from the bar, but the group of eight across the way were so loud it was impossible to hold dinner conversation, or even enjoy my meal (which tasted very good). I had to have it packed to go -- bummer. Can the restaurant really be held accountable for volume control? Maybe not completely, but a word from the manager as soon as the volume escalated may have helped. Afterward, we discovered from friends in the neighborhood that they had a similar experience. First visit was loud, but tolerable; second visit, they walked out (and other patrons did as well). They even talked to the owner -- "your food is great but we won't be back." I'm not writing this place off, though, because the food really was good and the overall service was good. And I'm not writing this review to prevent others from going, just to let you know that it's not the place for a romantic date or relaxing dinner with normal conversation. I may try again -- with my own loud group of eight. Or maybe sit at the bar, which was actually less noisy. If you do go, however, I recommend the artichoke appetizer and the fried calamari. The little bit I had of my seafood linguine was tasty, too.
